{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476783"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:51:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:51:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13947"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13947"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.08,0.08,0.67,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49631"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6577"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13947"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34902"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13277"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49631"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA group of three children, aged eight, 10, and 12 years, presents to the Emergency Department with similar symptoms. They all complain of nausea, severe vomiting, dizziness, and abdominal cramping that began approximately two hours after attending a birthday party. They report eating various foods at the party, including a cold rice dish that had been left out at room temperature for several hours. None of the children have any significant medical history or take any regular medications. On examination, they appear unwell with mild dehydration. Their vital signs are within normal limits except for mild tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most likely to be found in large numbers if the cold rice dish were to be analysed?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clostridium botulinum","Escherichia coli","Listeria monocytogenes","Bacillus cereus","Salmonella enterica"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely causative organism in this scenario is \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EBacillus cereus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E. This gram-positive, spore-forming bacterium is commonly associated with food poisoning from improperly stored starchy foods, particularly rice. The rapid onset of symptoms (within one to six hours) and the predominance of upper gastrointestinal symptoms (nausea and vomiting) are characteristic of \u003Cem\u003EB. cereus \u003C/em\u003Eintoxication. It\u0027s worth noting that \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E is another potential cause of rapid-onset food poisoning with a similar timeframe and symptom profile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ESalmonella enterica\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is also a common cause of food poisoning, but typically has a longer incubation period (12-72 hours) and is more often associated with contaminated eggs, poultry, or dairy products. Symptoms usually include diarrhoea, fever, and abdominal cramps.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E,\u003C/em\u003E particularly enterotoxigenic strains, can cause food poisoning, but is more commonly associated with contaminated water or undercooked ground beef. The incubation period is usually longer (one to three days), and bloody diarrhoea is a common symptom.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EClostridium botulinum\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E causes a rare but severe form of food poisoning (botulism). It\u0027s typically associated with improperly canned or preserved foods. Symptoms include neurological signs such as double vision, slurred speech, and muscle weakness, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EListeria monocytogenes\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E can contaminate various foods but is more commonly associated with unpasteurized dairy products, deli meats, and soft cheeses. It typically causes a more severe illness with a longer incubation period and can be particularly dangerous for pregnant women and immunocompromised individuals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bacillus cereus is a common cause of food poisoning associated with improperly stored starchy foods like rice, with a rapid onset of symptoms (one to six hours) including nausea, vomiting, and abdominal cramps.","Staphylococcus aureus is another potential cause of rapid-onset food poisoning, with a similar timeframe and symptom profile to Bacillus cereus."],"references":["Roberts I. Nelson\u2019s textbook of pediatrics (20th edn.) by Kliegman R, Stanton B, St. Geme J, Schor N (eds). 2017:1364\u20131365. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1007/s00247-017-3907-9","Granum PE, Lund T. Bacillus cereus and its food poisoning toxins. FEMS Microbiology Letters. 1997;157(2):223-8. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/femsle/article/157/2/223/620090","Bintsis T. Foodborne pathogens. AIMS Microbiol. 2017 Jun 29;3(3):529-563. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6604998/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34902"}},"question":{"data":{"typ